<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-180-570  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 180 570.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Decisions  March 1989 v21 n3 p47(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Where 4GLs fall short. (fourth-generation languages)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Emrick, Ronald.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A survey of 17 companies by GTE Service Corp and the InternationalFunction Point User Group shows that fourth-generation languages(4GLs) have not lived up to their promise of productivity gains.andO;Data submitted on 363 projects was analyzed using function-pointanalysis and the results show that the productivity of projectsusing 4GLs was not much better, and sometimes was worse, thanprojects using COBOL.andP;  Choice of language had less impact onproductivity than did other factors such as terminal responsetimes for developers, office size and privacy.andP;  The study showsthat as the size of the project increases, productivity decreasesno matter what language is used.andP;  The study also shows that 4GLapplications can place extreme demands on processing resources,cancelling any development savings.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   GTE Service Corp. (surveys).andO;Topic:     Fourth-Generation LanguagesSurveyInternational Function Point User GroupProductivityProgrammers.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Productivity by language. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>